data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution | Remove — check `token.IsCancellationRequested` instead |

### Why the original code breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. There is **no way to forcibly kill a managed thread** in modern .NET — cancellation must be **cooperative**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST check the token for cancellation to actually stop.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Tasks use the thread pool; no manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` | Blocking wait; cancellation handles the timeout |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` via constructor | Cooperative signal replaces forcible abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No abort to reset — cancellation is checked voluntarily |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must** receive and check the token |
| No disposal | `using var cts` | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers |

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — work doesn't know about cancellation
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must cooperate with the token
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => ExpensiveCalculation(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### The work itself must cooperate

This is the **critical paradigm shift**. The old code could kill any thread mid-execution. Cooperative cancellation only works if the work checks the token:

```csharp
// Example: a long-running loop that cooperates with cancellation
public List<Record> ExpensiveCalculation(CancellationToken token)
{
    var results = new List<Record>();
    foreach (var item in LargeDataSet)
    {
        // Check at regular intervals — this is where cancellation happens
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();

        results.Add(Process(item));
    }
    return results;
}
```

### Key pitfalls for this specific migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Token ignored = timeout broken** | If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion regardless of timeout. The old `Thread.Abort` didn't need cooperation — the new model does. Audit every work delegate. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep(5000)` inside `work` won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000)` or `await Task.Delay(5000, token)`. |
| **Token not passed through call chain** | Every method called by `work` that does I/O or loops must forward the token. One missing link and cancellation stalls at that point. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using`/dispose it. The timeout constructor starts an internal timer — leaking it leaks the timer. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures we only catch our own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation from an outer scope. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If you call a third-party library that can't accept a token (e.g., a native FFI call), move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent to the old `Thread.Abort`. |
